  stimulus_text = 'The author''s main argument is that the way we see the world can be influenced by our personal experiences and beliefs. The author writes, "Our beliefs about the world, however unfounded, shape our perception of it, leading us to see what we want to see, rather than what is actually there." The author then provides examples of how this can happen in everyday life, such as when people see patterns in random data, or when they interpret ambiguous events in a way that confirms their existing biases. What is the author''s central point in this passage?',
