  stimulus_text = 'The American poet Langston Hughes was a central figure in the Harlem Renaissance. His work often explored the experiences of African Americans living in the United States, particularly in Harlem, a neighborhood in New York City that was a focal point of Black culture in the 1920s and 1930s. Hughes''s poems often celebrated Black culture and heritage, but they also addressed the challenges and injustices faced by African Americans. In his poem "The Weary Blues," Hughes captures the spirit of a blues musician playing in Harlem, a city where African American culture thrived, and he uses a simple, direct style that reflects the music''s rhythms and emotions. What is the main idea of the text?',
